es is both an introductory reference work and an original study which explores some of the most exciting new directions currently being opened up in cultural studies. A new generation has begun to emerge from the shadow of the Birmingham School: a generation who have turned to theory as a means to think through some of the crucial problems and issues in contemporary culture. New Cultural Studies: Adventures in Theory collects for the first time the ideas of this generation and explains just why theory continues to be crucial for cultural studies. The book explores theory's past, present and most especially future role in cultural studies. It does so by providing an authoritative and accessible guide, for students and researchers alike, to:some of the most interesting members of this 'post-Birmingham school' generationthe thinkers and theories currently influencing new work in cultural studies: Agamben, Badiou, Deleuze, Derrida, Hardt and Negri, Kittler, Laclau, Levinas, Zizekthe new territories being mapped out across the intersections of cultural studies and cultural theory: anti-capitalism, ethics, the posthumanities, post-Marxism, new media technologies, the transnational.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCulturexStudy and teaching. 0aCulture. 4aFilm, Media & Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBadmington, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBassett, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirchall, Clare, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBirchall, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoothroyd, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowman, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 